    "## 7. Notes and Next Steps\n",
    "\n",
    "### Methodological notes\n",
    "- The scraper uses polite rate limiting (default 2s between requests) and respects `robots.txt`. Some operators may block automated access; manual review of blocked pages is recommended.\n",
    "- JavaScript-rendered content is **not** captured by this scraper (it uses `requests` + `BeautifulSoup`). Operators that deliver content via React/Vue SPAs will require a Selenium or Playwright-based scraper — see `TODO` below.\n",
    "- Meta descriptions and page titles are under editorial control: they are the most deliberately crafted elements of the page and should be treated as primary discourse data, not mere metadata.\n",
    "\n",
    "### TODO items\n",
    "1. [ ] Add a JavaScript-rendering fallback (Playwright) for SPA-heavy operators\n",
    "2. [ ] Implement temporal tracking — re-scrape quarterly to detect narrative shifts\n",
    "3. [ ] Expand config CSV with full list of operators (target: 20+ for cross-sectional analysis)\n",
    "4. [ ] Code image alt tags into thematic categories (Section 4)\n",
    "5. [ ] Build facility link network graph (Section 5)\n",
    "6. [ ] Connect to WP2 satellite imagery: do facility links lead to photographable locations?\n",
    "7. [ ] Cross-reference facility URLs with known data center coordinates (DCD, BroadGroup, CBRE)\n",
    "\n",
    "### References\n",
    "- Holt, J., & Vonderau, P. (2015). 'Where the Internet Lives': Data Centers as Cloud Infrastructure. *Signal Traffic: Critical Studies of Media Infrastructures.*\n",
    "- Mosco, V. (2014). *To the Cloud: Big Data in a Turbulent World.* Paradigm.\n",
    "- Amoore, L. (2018). Cloud Geographies: Computing, Data, Sovereignty. *Progress in Human Geography.*"
   ]
  }
 ]
